// ANGLE.xcconfig — Enable OpenGL ES via ANGLE (Metal backend) on macOS desktop
//
// ANGLE now ships through the `xLights-spm` Swift package (product "ANGLE"),
// which is already registered on this project. The iPad target links it
// unconditionally; the desktop build keeps it opt-in via this xcconfig.
//
// To enable ANGLE/GLES for ShaderEffect on the desktop xLights target:
// 1. Add the "ANGLE" package product to the xLights target:
//    xLights target > General > Frameworks, Libraries, and Embedded Content >
//    + > ANGLE (from the xLights-spm package).
// 2. Set this xcconfig in Xcode:
//    Project > Info > Configurations > set this file for Debug/Release/Archive.
//
// To revert to desktop OpenGL: remove the xcconfig from the project
// configurations and remove the ANGLE product from the xLights target.
//
// The SPM macOS binary targets keep their @rpath/<name>.dylib id, so Xcode
// links and embeds them automatically — no build_angle.sh and no manual
// mac_fix_dylibs embedding step are needed anymore.

GCC_PREPROCESSOR_DEFINITIONS = $(inherited) USE_GLES=1

// gl* symbol resolution — the macOS analog of the Windows opengl32-shadowing
// problem.  wx's GL lib pulls in Apple's OpenGL.framework, which exports the
// same gl* names (glGetString, glDrawArrays, …) as ANGLE's libGLESv2.  In the
// two-level namespace, each undefined gl* binds to the FIRST linked provider,
// and the ANGLE SPM product links AFTER -framework OpenGL — so gl* bound to
// Apple's OpenGL and crashed when called under an ANGLE EGL context (Apple GL
// has no current CGL context).  Prepending the ANGLE libs into OTHER_LDFLAGS
// puts them ahead of -framework OpenGL so gl* binds to ANGLE; CGL*/AGL* (only
// in OpenGL.framework, used by wx's dead-on-Metal GL canvas) still resolve
// there.  egl* already bind correctly (only ANGLE provides them).
OTHER_LDFLAGS = -lGLESv2 -lEGL
